# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: eaza-ex-situ-programme
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/blue-listed] The concept of a Blue List was derived in 1971 by Robert Arbib from the National Audubon Society in his article, "Announcing-- The Blue List: an 'early warning' system for birds".
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/blue-listed] The article stated that the list was made up for species that appear to be locally common in North America, but is undergoing non-cyclic declines.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/blue-listed] Starting from 1971, it was utilized to list vulnerable bird species throughout North America.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/blue-listed] Unlike the US Fish and Wildlife Endangered Species List, the Blue List was made to identify **patterns** of population losses for regional bird populations before they could be listed as endangered.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/blue-listed] Every decade after its release, the list is revisited and revised based on regional editors and species get "nominated" to be added to the list.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/blue-listed] Using this metric reginal editors were able to report on the species along with their status ranks in order to identify the patterns of population growth that each species is facing.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] A **breed registry**, also known as a **herdbook**, **studbook** or **register**, in animal husbandry, the hobby of animal fancy, is an official list of animals within a specific breed whose parents are known.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] Animals are usually registered by their breeders while they are young.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] The terms studbook and register are also used to refer to lists of male animals "standing at stud", that is, those animals actively breeding, as opposed to every known specimen of that breed.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] Such registries usually issue certificates for each recorded animal, called a **pedigree**, **pedigreed animal documentation**, or most commonly, an animal's "**papers**".
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] Registration papers may consist of a simple certificate or a listing of ancestors in the animal's background, sometimes with a pedigree chart showing the lineage.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] There are breed registries and breed clubs for several species of animal, such as dogs, horses, cows and cats.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] The *European Association of Zoos and Aquaria* (EAZA) and the US *Association of Zoos and Aquariums* (AZA) also maintains stud books for captive species on display ranging from aardvarks to zebras.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] Kennel clubs always maintain registries, either directly or through affiliated dog breed clubs.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] Some multi-breed clubs also maintain registries, as do non-affiliated breed clubs, and there are a few registries that are maintained by other private entities such as insurance agencies; an example of this in the United States is the Field Dog Stud Book.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] Working dog organizations also maintain registries.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] There are also entities that refer to themselves as registries, but that are thinly veiled marketing devices for vendors of puppies and adult dogs, as well as a means of collecting registration fees from novice dog owners unfamiliar with reputable registries and breed clubs.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] Although these entities generally focus on dogs, particularly in relationship to the puppy mill industry, some are marketed as cat registries.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] At least one group claims to register wild species (held by private individuals rather than by legitimate zoological parks, which use the AZA).
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] Horse breeding also has such problematic registries, particularly for certain color breeds.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] While many color breeds are legitimate, some "registries" are primarily a marketing tool for poor quality animals that are not accepted for registration by more mainstream organizations.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] Other "registries" are marketing attempts to create new horse breeds, usually by breeders using crossbreeding to create a new type, but the animals are not yet breeding true.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] Many such questionable registries are incorporated as for-profit commercial businesses, in contrast to the formal not-for-profit status of most reputable breed clubs.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] They may provide volume discounts for registrations by commercial dog breeders such as puppy mills.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] An unscrupulous registry for dogs or horses is often spotted by a policy to not require any proof of pedigree at all.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] In the dog world, such registries may not sponsor competitions and thus cannot award championship points to identify the best individuals registered within a particular breed or species.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] In the less-organized world of horse shows, where many different sanctioning organizations exist, some groups sponsor their own competitions, though wins at such events seldom carry much prestige in mainstream circles.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] Some registers have the word "registry" in their title used in the sense of "list"; these entities are not registers in the usual sense in that they do not maintain breeding records.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] In the dog world, listed animals are required to be de-sexed.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] The American Mixed Breed Obedience Registry is an example.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] Some equestrian organizations create a recording system for tracking the competition records of horses, but, though horses of any sex may be recorded, they also do not maintain breeding or progeny records.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] The United States Equestrian Federation is one organization that uses such a system.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] A closed stud book is a stud book or breed registry that does not accept any outside blood.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] The registered animals and all subsequent offspring trace back to the foundation stock.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] This ensures that the animal is a purebred member of the breed.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] In horses, an example of a closed stud book is that of the Thoroughbred, with a stud book tracing to 1791.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] For the breed to move to the Miscellaneous class and then to fully recognized status, the breed's stud book must be closed.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] A closed stud book allows the breed to stay very pure to its type, but limits its ability to be improved.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] For instance, in performance disciplines, an animal that is successful in competitions is generally worth more than one that is pure.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] It also limits the gene pool, which may make certain undesirable characteristics become accentuated in the breed, such as a poor conformational fault or a disease.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] Some closed stud books, particularly for certain European breeds such as the Finnhorse and the Trakehner, may also have a set of studbook selection criteria where animals must meet either a conformation standard, a performance standard, or both.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] In an open stud book, animals may be registered even if their parents or earlier ancestors were not previously registered with that particular entity.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] Usually an open stud book has strict studbook selection criteria that require an animal to meet a certain standard of conformation, performance or both.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] This allows breeders to modify breeds by including individuals who conform to the breed standard but are of outside origin.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] Some horse breeds allow crossbreds who meet specific criteria to be registered.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] One example is the semi-open stud book of the American Quarter Horse, which still accepts horses of Thoroughbred breeding, particularly via its appendix registry.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] Among dogs, an example of an open stud book would be the registries maintained by the American Kennel Club as its Foundation Stock Service.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] In some cases, an open stud book may eventually become closed once the breed type is deemed to be fully set.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] In some agricultural breeds, an otherwise closed registry includes a *grading up* route for the incorporation of cross-bred animals.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] Often such incorporation is limited to females, with the progeny only being accepted as full pedigree animals after several generations of breeding to full-blood males.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] Such mechanisms may also allow the incorporation of purebred animals descended from unregistered stock or of uncertain parentage.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] More controversial open stud books are those where there are few, if any qualifications for animals other than a single trait, such as a "color breed," particularly when the color is not a true-breeding characteristic.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] However, some breeds have a standard color or color preference that is one criterion among others used to register animals.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] Some open or partly open registries may permit animals who have some but not all qualifications for full registration to nonetheless be entered in a preliminary recording system often called an "appendix" registry.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] The most notable is that of the American Quarter Horse Association, which allows part-Thoroughbred/part-Quarter Horse foals to be recorded and shown, with full registration allowed after the horse achieves a set performance or merit standard akin to that of a merit registry.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] Another form of open registry is a registry based on performance or conformation, called in some societies *Registry on Merit.* In such registries, an eligible animal that meets certain criteria is eligible to be registered *on merit,* regardless of ancestry.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] In some cases, even unknown or undocumented ancestry may be permitted.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] The Registry on Merit or ROM may be tied to percentage of bloodline, conformation, or classification or may be based solely on performance.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] In the horse world, many warmblood breed organizations require a conformation and performance standard for registration, and often allow horses of many different breeds to qualify, though documented pedigrees are usually required.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] Some breed registries use a form of ROM in which horses at certain shows may be sight classified.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] For example, at qualifying shows in Australia, winning horses of stock-type breeding receive points for conformation, which are attested to by the judges and recorded in an owner's special book.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] The points are accumulated to eventually result in a Registry on Merit.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] Registry on Merit is prevalent with sheepdog registries, in particular those of the Border Collie, and some other breeds with a heavy emphasis on working ability.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] In this type of ROM, the dog's conformation and ancestry generally does not matter.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] Breed registries usually issue certificates for each recorded animal, called a *pedigree*, *pedigreed animal documentation*, or most commonly, an animal's "papers".
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] Usually, there is space for the listing of successive owners, who must sign and date the document if the animal is gifted, leased or sold.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] Papers transferred upon sale of an animal may be submitted to the registry in order to update the ownership information, and in most cases, the registry will then issue a new set of papers listing the new owner as the proper owner of the horse.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] Genuine papers are often identifiable as containing the registered name and number of the individual animal and its date of birth, the name of the attesting organization, with the logo if there is one, the name and signature of the registrar or other authorized person, and a corporate stamp or seal.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] Registration papers are sometimes used as certificates of title.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] In some registries, breeders may apply for permission to crossbreed other breeds into the line to emphasize certain traits, to keep the breed from extinction or to alleviate problems caused in the breed by inbreeding from a limited set of animals.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] A related preservation method is backbreeding, used by some equine and canine registries, in which crossbred individuals are mated back to purebreds to eliminate undesirable traits acquired through the crossbreeding.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] Naming rules vary according to the species and breed being registered.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] Along with a registered name, these animals often also have a simpler "pet name" known as a call name for dogs or a stable name for horses, which is used by their owners or handlers when talking to the animal.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] For example, the famous Thoroughbred race horse Man o' War was known by his stable name, "Big Red." The name can be anything that the animal's owner prefers.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] For example, the dog that won the 2008 Westminster show (US) was named K-Run's Park Me In First, with the call name of "Uno".
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] Dogs in the breed registry of a working dog club (particularly herding dogs) must usually have simple, no-nonsense monikers deemed to be "working dog names" such as "Pal", "Blackie", or "Ginger".
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] The naming rules for independent dog clubs vary but are usually similar to those of kennel clubs.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] The registered name often refers directly or indirectly to the breeder of the animal.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] Traditionally, the breeder's kennel prefix forms the first part of the dog's registered name.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] For example, all dogs bred at the Gold Mine Kennels would have names that begin with the words "Gold Mine".
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] Horse breeders are usually not required to do this, but often find it to be a good form of commercial promotion to include a stable name or farm initials in the horse's name.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] For example, Gold Mine Stables may name give all horses names with the prefix "Gold Mine", "GM", or "GMS".
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] The Jockey Club, which registers Thoroughbreds in Great Britain, requires stable names to be registered, but does not require their use in animal names.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] Many dog breeders name their puppies sequentially, based on litter identification: Groups of puppies may be organized as Litter A, Litter B, and so on.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] When this is done, the names of all the puppies in litter A start with the letter "A," then "B" for litter B and so on.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] Horse breeders, especially in Europe, sometimes use the first letter of the dam's name as the first letter in the name of all of her offspring.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] Other breeders may use the same first letter to designate all the foals born on the farm in a given year.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] Some breeders create a name that incorporates or acknowledges the names of the sire, dam or other forebears.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] For example, the famous cutting horse Doc O'Lena was by Doc Bar out of Poco Lena, a daughter of Poco Bueno.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] Some names are a little less direct: 2003 Kentucky Derby winner Funny Cide was by Distorted Humor out of Belle's Good Cide, and the famous race horse Native Dancer was by Polynesian out of Geisha.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] For example, a more imaginative breeder at the Gold Mine Kennels might name all the puppies of one litter after green precious stones: Gold Mine Emerald, Gold Mine Jade, and Gold Mine Peridot.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] Names for a subsequent litter might start with the adjectives describing precious stones: Gold Mine Sparkle, Gold Mine Brilliance, and Gold Mine Chatoyant.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] Breeders may be as creative or as mundane as they wish.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] In order to minimize the unwieldiness that long and fancy names can bring, registries usually limit the total number of characters and sometimes number of separate words that may compose the animal's registered name.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] They are often prohibited from using only punctuation or odd capitalization to create a unique name; names are often published in all capitals on registration papers.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] Breeders are generally not allowed to use any name that may be obscene or misleading, such as the word 'champion' in a name, a trademark, or anything that can be mistaken for the name of another kennel or, sometimes, stable.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] Only after an animal has achieved a legitimate championship will some registries permit the use of the prefix Ch., or other title before or after their registered name.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] Some registries may use symbols to designate the status of certain individuals.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] An asterisk * may be used to designate an animal born in another country and imported.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/breed-registry] A plus + may be used to designate a champion or an animal under special registration status.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] For many species, relatively little is known about the conditions needed for successful breeding.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Information about a species' reproductive biology may be critical to the success of a captive breeding program.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] In some cases a captive breeding program can save a species from extinction, but for success, breeders must consider many factors—including genetic, ecological, behavioral, and ethical issues.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Most successful attempts involve the cooperation and coordination of many institutions.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] The efforts put into captive breeding can aid in education about conservation because species in captivity are closer to the public than their wild conspecifics.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] These accomplishments from the continued breeding of species for generations in captivity is also aided by extensive research efforts ex-situ and in-situ.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Captive breeding techniques began with the first human domestication of animals such as goats, and plants like wheat, at least 10,000 years ago.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] These practices were expanded with the rise of the first zoos, which started as royal menageries such as the one at Hierakonpolis, capital in the Predynastic Period of Egypt.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] The first actual captive breeding programs were only started in the 1960s.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] These programs, such as the Arabian Oryx breeding program from the Phoenix Zoo in 1962, were aimed at the reintroduction of these species into the wild.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] These programs expanded under The Endangered Species Act of 1973 of the Nixon Administration which focused on protecting endangered species and their habitats to preserve biodiversity.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Since then, research and conservation have been housed in zoos, such as the Institute for Conservation Research at the San Diego Zoo founded in 1975 and expanded in 2009, which have contributed to the successful conservation efforts of species such as the Hawaiian Crow.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] The breeding of species of conservation concern is coordinated by cooperative breeding programs containing international studbooks and coordinators, who evaluate the roles of individual animals and institutions from a global or regional perspective.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] These studbooks contain information on birth date, gender, location, and lineage (if known), which helps determine survival and reproduction rates, number of founders of the population, and inbreeding coefficients.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] A species coordinator reviews the information in studbooks and determines a breeding strategy that would produce most advantageous offspring.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] If two compatible animals are found at different zoos, the animals may be transported for mating, but this is stressful, which could in turn make mating less likely.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] However, this is still a popular breeding method among European zoological organizations.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Artificial fertilization (by shipping semen) is another option, but male animals can experience stress during semen collection, and the same goes for females during the artificial insemination procedure.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Furthermore, this approach yields lower-quality semen, because shipping requires extending the life of the sperm for the transit time.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] The objective of many captive populations is to hold similar levels of genetic diversity to what is found in wild populations.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] As captive populations are usually small and maintained in artificial environments, genetics factors such as adaptation, inbreeding and loss of diversity can be a major concern.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Adaptive differences between plant and animal populations arise due to variations in environmental pressures.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] In the case of captive breeding prior to reintroduction into the wild, it is possible for species to evolve to adapt to the captive environment, rather than their natural environment.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Reintroducing a plant or animal to an environment dissimilar to the one they were originally from can cause fixation of traits that may not be suited for that environment leaving the individual disadvantaged.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Selection intensity, initial genetic diversity, and effective population size can impact how much the species adapts to its captive environment.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Modeling works indicate that the duration of the programs (i.e., time from the foundation of the captive population to the last release event) is an important determinant of reintroduction success.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Success is maximized for intermediate project duration allowing the release of a sufficient number of individuals, while minimizing the number of generations undergoing relaxed selection in captivity.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Can be minimized by reducing the number of generations in captivity, minimizing selection for captive adaptations by creating environment similar to natural environment and maximizing the number of immigrants from wild populations.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] One consequence of small captive population size is the increased impact of genetic drift, where genes have the potential to fix or disappear completely by chance, thereby reducing genetic diversity.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Other factors that can impact genetic diversity in a captive population are bottlenecks and initial population size.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Bottlenecks, such as rapid decline in the population or a small initial population impacts genetic diversity.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Loss can be minimized by establishing a population with a large enough number of founders to genetically represent the wild population, maximize population size, maximize ratio of effective population size to actual population size, and minimize the number of generations in captivity.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Inbreeding is when organisms mate with closely related individuals, lowering heterozygosity in a population.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Although inbreeding can be relatively common, when it results in a reduction in fitness it is known as inbreeding depression.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] The detrimental effects of inbreeding depression are especially prevalent in smaller populations and can therefore be extensive in captive populations.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] To make these populations the most viable, it is important to monitor and reduce the effects of deleterious allele expression caused by inbreeding depression and to restore genetic diversity.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Comparing inbred populations against non-inbred or less-inbred populations can help determine the extent of detrimental effects if any are present.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Closely monitoring the possibility of inbreeding within the captive bred population is also key to the success of reintroduction into the species' native habitat.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Outbreeding is when organisms mate with unrelated individuals, increasing heterozygosity in a population.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Although new diversity is often beneficial, if there are large genetic differences between the two individuals it can result in outbreeding depression.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] This is a reduction in fitness, similar to that of inbreeding depression, but arises from a number of different mechanisms, including taxonomic issues, chromosomal differences, sexual incompatibility, or adaptive differences between the individuals.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] A common cause is chromosomal ploidy differences and hybridization between individuals leading to sterility.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] The best example is in the orangutan, which, prior to taxonomic revisions in the 1980s would be commonly mated in captive populations producing hybrid orangutans with lower fitness.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] If chromosomal ploidy is ignored during reintroduction, restoration efforts would fail due to sterile hybrids in the wild.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] If there are large genetic differences between individuals originally from distant populations, those individuals should only be bred in circumstances where no other mates exist.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Captive breeding can contribute to changes in behavior in animals that have been reintroduced to the wild.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Released animals are commonly less capable of hunting or foraging for food, which leads to starvation, possibly because the young animals spent the critical learning period in captivity.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Released animals often display more risk-taking behavior and fail to avoid predators.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Golden lion tamarin mothers often die in the wild before having offspring because they cannot climb and forage.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] This leads to continuing population declines despite reintroduction as the species are unable to produce viable offspring.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Training can improve anti-predator skills, but its effectiveness varies.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Salmon bred in captivity have shown similar declines in caution and are killed by predators when young.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] However, salmon that were reared in an enriched environment with natural prey showed less risk-taking behaviors and were more likely to survive.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] A study on mice has found that after captive breeding had been in place for multiple generations and these mice were "released" to breed with wild mice, that the captive-born mice bred amongst themselves instead of with the wild mice.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] This suggests that captive breeding may affect mating preferences, and has implications for the success of a reintroduction program.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Human mediated recovery of species can unintentionally promote maladaptive behaviors in wild populations.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] In 1980 the number of wild Chatham Island Black Robins was reduced to a single mating pair.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Intense management of populations helped the population recover and by 1998 there were 200 individuals.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] During recovery scientists observed "rim laying" an egg laying habit where individuals laid eggs on the rim of the nest instead of the center.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] To combat this land managers pushed the egg to the center of the nest, which greatly increased reproduction.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] However, by allowing this maladaptive trait to persist, over half the population were now rim layers.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Genetic studies found that this was an autosomal dominant mendelian trait that was selected for due to human intervention.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Another challenge presented to captive breeding is an attempt to establish multi-partner mating systems in captive populations.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] It can be difficult to replicate the circumstances surrounding multiple mate systems and allow it to occur naturally in captivity due to limited housing space and lack of information.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] When brought into captivity, there is no guarantee that a pair of animals will pair bond or that all the members of a population will participate in breeding.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Throughout facilities, there is limited housing space so allowing for mate choice may establish genetic issues in the population.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] A lack of information surrounding the effects of mating systems on captive populations can also present issues when attempting to breed.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] These mating systems are not always fully understood and the effects captivity may have on them cannot be known until they are studied in greater capacity.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] The Phoenix Zoo had an Arabian Oryx breeding program in 1962.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] They were able to successfully breed over 200 individuals from a lineage of only 9 original founders.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Members from this founding population were then sent to many other facilities worldwide, and many breeding herds were established.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] In 1982, the first of the population was reintroduced back into Oman, and over the next two decades, their population increased over time and was able to successfully reestablish in native regions.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Arabian Oryx have now been reintroduced into areas such as Saudi Arabia, Oman, and Israel and they now number 1,100, showing a recovery thanks to captive breeding efforts.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] The De Wildt Cheetah and Wildlife Centre, established in South Africa in 1971, has a cheetah captive breeding program.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Between 1975 and 2005, 242 litters were born with a total of 785 cubs.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] The survival rate of cubs was 71.3% for the first twelve months and 66.2% for older cubs, validating the fact that cheetahs can be bred successfully (and their endangerment decreased).
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] It also indicated that failure in other breeding habitats may be due to "poor" sperm morphology.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Przewalski's horse, the only horse species never to have been domesticated, was recovered from the brink of extinction by a captive breeding program, and successfully reintroduced in the 1990s to the Mongolia, with more than 750 wild roaming Przewalski's horses as of 2020.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] The Galápagos tortoise population, once reaching as low in population as 12 remaining individuals, as of 2014 was recovered to more than 2000 by a captive breeding program.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] A further 8 tortoise species were supported by captive breeding programs in the island chain.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Wild Tasmanian devils have declined by 90% due to a transmissible cancer called Devil Facial Tumor Disease.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] A captive insurance population program was started, but the captive breeding rates as of 2012 were lower than they needed to be.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Keeley, Fanson, Masters, and McGreevy (2012) sought to "increase our understanding of the estrous cycle of the devil and elucidate potential causes of failed male-female pairings" by examining temporal patterns of fecal progestogen and corticosterone metabolite concentrations.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] They found that the majority of unsuccessful females were captive-born, suggesting that if the species' survival depended solely on captive breeding, the population would probably disappear.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] In 2010, the Oregon Zoo found that Columbia Basin pygmy rabbit pairings based on familiarity and preferences resulted in a significant increase in breeding success.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] In 2019, researchers trying to breed captive American paddlefish and Russian sturgeon separately inadvertently bred sturddlefish - a hybrid fish between the two fish.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Captive breeding can also be a research tool to understand the reproductive physiology and reproductive behaviors of species.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] In order to successfully breed animals, there must be an understanding of their mating systems, their reproductive physiology, and behavior or mating rituals.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Through captive breeding programs, these factors can be measured in a finite setting and the results can be interpreted and used to aid in ex-situ and in-situ conservation.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Through a greater understanding of these systems, captive breeding efforts can have greater success when attempting to reproduce a species.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] A lot of research about elephant reproductive physiology and estrus cycles has been conducted in captivity and a greater understanding of how these factors play into breeding attempts can be established.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Behavioral research quantifies the effects of how estrus plays a role in the herds behaviors and how this effects the bulls of a herd.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] This research can help facilities monitor for behavior changes in their herd and conduct successful breeding attempts through this understanding.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Research helps with better understanding these physiological systems which in turn helps increase successful breeding attempts and allows for more generations to be brought up in captivity.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Not only does physiological research aid in captive breeding attempts, but multi-generational research is also another important research tool that is conducted on different species and genetic changes can be tracked through different lineages brought up in captivity.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Genetic changes throughout a specific lineage can help provide breeding recommendations and allow for genetic diversity within a captive population to remain high.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] This genetic record keeping is also used in order to understand phylogeny and to better understand fitness changes that may occur over generations in captive populations.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] This form of record keeping helps aid in research surrounding population genetics in order to evaluate the best method to sustain high genetic variation within captive populations.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Research conducted on captive breeding populations is also important when creating SAFE's and SSP's for a certain species.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Studies in behavior are important when developing captive breeding programs because they allow facilities to understand an animals response to captivity and allows facilities to adapt proper housing conditions for the animals.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Populations that are currently being propagated in captivity are very important research tools for understanding how to carry out successful propagation of a certain species.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] This research allows the knowledge to be passed on to more facilities allowing for more breeding programs to be developed in order to increase the genetic diversity of captive populations.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] The research conducted on breeding populations is also an important gateway into understanding other aspects of an animal such as social dynamics, nutrition and diet requirements, and demographics to allow for captive populations to prosper.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] To found a captive breeding population with adequate genetic diversity, breeders usually select individuals from different source populations—ideally, at least 20–30 individuals.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Founding populations for captive breeding programs have often had fewer individuals than ideal because of their threatened state, leaving them more susceptible to challenges such as inbreeding depression.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] To overcome challenges of captive breeding such as adaptive differences, loss of genetic diversity, inbreeding depression, and outbreeding depression and get desired results, captive breeding programs use many monitoring methods.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Artificial insemination is used to produce the desired offspring from individuals who do not mate naturally to reduce effects of mating closely related individuals such as inbreeding.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Methods as seen in panda pornography allow programs to mate chosen individuals by encouraging mating behavior.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] A concern in captive breeding is to minimize the effects of breeding closely related individuals, microsatellite regions from an organism's genome can be used to determine amounts of relationship among founders to minimize relatedness and pick the most distant individuals to breed.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] This method has successfully been used in the captive breeding of the California condor and the Guam rail.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] The maximum avoidance of inbreeding (MAI) scheme allows control at a group level rather than an individual level by rotating individuals between groups to avoid inbreeding.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Facilities can use intensive housing compared to group housing to allow for easier reproductive success and create more genetic diversity within a population.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Intensive housing is when a species is forced into monogamy so only two individuals mate with each other, compared to group housing where the entire population is kept in the same space to try and replicate multi-partner breeding systems.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] When using intensive housing and forcing monogamy to take place, it is seen that inbreeding is lowered and a greater genetic diversity results.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Intensive housing efforts were used with Tasmanian Devil populations in captivity compared to allowing for group mate choice.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] This helped increase the populations reproductive success in captivity and saw less inbreeding depression within the population.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Using intensive housing to help establish a genetically healthy population in captivity can allow facilities to further increase conservation efforts of a species and combat genetic issues that may arise in the captive population.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Getting captive wild animals to breed naturally can be a difficult task.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Giant pandas for example lose interest in mating once they are captured, and female giant pandas only experience estrus once a year, which only lasts for 48 to 72 hours.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Many researchers have turned to artificial insemination in an attempt to increase the populations of endangered animals.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] It may be used for many reasons, including to overcome physical breeding difficulties, to allow a male to inseminate a much larger number of females, to control the paternity of offspring, and to avoid injury incurred during natural mating.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] It also creates more genetically diverse captive populations, enabling captive facilities to easily share genetic material with each other without the need to move animals.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Scientist of the Justus-Liebig-University of Giessen, Germany, from the working group of Michael Lierz, developed a novel technique for semen collection and artificial insemination in parrots producing the world's first macaw by assisted reproduction.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Animal species can be preserved in gene banks, which consist of a cryogenic facilities used to store live sperm, eggs, or embryos in ultracold conditions.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] The Zoological Society of San Diego has established a "frozen zoo" to store frozen tissue from the world's rarest and most endangered species samples using cryopreservation techniques.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] At present, there has been more than 355 species, including mammals, reptiles, and birds.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Cryopreservation can be performed as oocyte cryopreservation before fertilization, or as embryo cryopreservation after fertilization.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Cryogenically preserved specimens can potentially be used to revive breeds that are endangered or extinct, for breed improvement, crossbreeding, research and development.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] This method can be used for virtually indefinite storage of material without deterioration over a much greater time-period relative to all other methods of *ex situ* conservation.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] However, cryo-conservation can be an expensive strategy and requires long term hygienic and economic commitment for germplasms to remain viable.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Cryo-conservation can also face unique challenges based on the species, as some species have a reduced survival rate of frozen germplasm, but cryobiology is a field of active research and many studies concerning plants are underway.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] An example of the use of cryoconservation to prevent the extinction of a livestock breed is the case of the Hungarian Grey cattle, or Magya Szurke.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Hungarian Grey cattle were once a dominant breed in southeastern Europe with a population of 4.9 million head in 1884.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] They were mainly used for draft power and meat.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] However, the population had decreased to 280,000 head by the end of World War II and eventually reached the low population of 187 females and 6 males from 1965 to 1970.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] The breed's decreased use was due primarily to the mechanization of agriculture and the adoption of major breeds, which yield higher milk production.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] The Hungarian government launched a project to preserve the breed, as it possesses valuable traits, such as stamina, calving ease, disease resistance, and easy adaptation to a variety of climates.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] The government program included various conservation strategies, including the cryopreservation of semen and embryos.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] The Hungarian government's conservation effort brought the population up to 10,310 in 2012, which shows significant improvement using cryoconservation.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] The best current cloning techniques have an average success rate of 9.4 percent, when working with familiar species such as mice, while cloning wild animals is usually less than 1 percent successful.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] In 2001, a cow named Bessie gave birth to a cloned Asian gaur, an endangered species, but the calf died after two days.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] In 2003, a banteng was successfully cloned, followed by three African wildcats from a thawed frozen embryo.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] These successes provided hope that similar techniques (using surrogate mothers of another species) might be used to clone extinct species.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Anticipating this possibility, tissue samples from the last bucardo (Pyrenean ibex) were frozen in liquid nitrogen immediately after it died in 2000.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Researchers are also considering cloning endangered species such as the giant panda and cheetah.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] However, cloning of animals is opposed by animal-groups due to the number of cloned animals that suffer from malformations before they die.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] A potential technique for aiding in reproduction of endangered species is interspecific pregnancy, implanting embryos of an endangered species into the womb of a female of a related species, carrying it to term.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] It has been used for the Spanish Ibex and Houbara bustard.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Captive breeding is an important tool used in modern education of conservation issues because it provides a framework for how we care about species and allows institutions to show the beauty that is contained in our natural environment.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] These practices of captive breeding can be used to explain the function of the modern-day facilities and their importance in conservation.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Through continued breeding efforts populations can continue to be displayed in closer proximity to the public and their role in conservation can be explained.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] These explanations help show a side of the world many people will not engage with because conservation is not something that is inherently known about, it must be shown and taught to others to raise awareness of the issues around the globe.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] By allowing people to view these species in captivity, it allows facilities to explain the issues they face in the wild and advocate for the conservation of these species and their natural habitats.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Institutions focus efforts on large charismatic species, such as elephants, giraffes, rhinos etc., because these draw more visitors to institutions and garner more attention from the public.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] While a lot of these charismatic megafauna do draw more attention than other species, we can still use captive breeding programs and facilities involving other species to educate the public about a broader range of issues.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Bristol Zoo Gardens in the United Kingdom has maintained a species of medicinal leech (*Hirudo medicinalis*) in their facility to use as an education exhibit.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Leeches normally have a negative connotation surrounded by them but they have been used as an important tool in medicine.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] The display at Bristol Zoo Gardens provides an educational piece and tells the story of a woman who sold leeches to the locals around her for medicinal purposes.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] This display advocates for a smaller species that would not normally be covered by facilities, but they are well maintained in this facility and are active conservation of the species is being done because of its significance around humans and in the environment.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] With successes, captive-breeding programs have proven successful throughout history.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Notable examples include the American black-footed ferret; in 1986, a dwindling wild population of only 18 was eventually raised to 500.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] From these actions, those eleven oryx were successfully bred from the brink of extinction, and would go on to be re-released in the deserts of Jordan, Oman, Bahrain, United Arab Emirates and Qatar.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Starting in 1980, the first animals were set free.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Currently, the wild animals number around 1,000 individuals, with a further 6,000-7,000 in zoos and breeding centres internationally.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] While captive breeding can be an ideal solution for preventing endangered animals from facing serious threats of extinction there are still reasons why these programs can occasionally do more harm than good.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Although it has been proven that captive breeding programs have yielded negative genetic effects in decreasing the fitness of captive-bred organisms, there is no direct evidence to show that this negative effect also decreases the overall fitness of their wild-born descendants.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Additionally, there are many ethical complications to reintroducing animals born in captivity back into the wild.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] For example, when scientists were reintroducing a rare species of toad back into the Mallorcan wild in 1993, a potentially deadly fungus that could kill frogs and toads was unintentionally introduced.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] It is also important to maintain the organism's original habitat, or replicate that specific habitat for species survival.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] There are ethical issues surrounding if a species truly needs human intervention and if the resources going toward the captive breeding of these species cannot be allocated to other areas.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Some populations may not need intervention because they were never extinction-prone in the first place such as the peregrine falcon.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] The population of peregrine falcons had a crash in the 1950s and 1960s due to the effect of pesticides on egg production and species survival, causing a decline in the population.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] Many facilities at the time in the U.S. and in European countries brought in peregrine falcons in order to help their declining population and establish a steady population through captive breeding.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] It was later shown through research conducted on the reproductive success of Peregrine Falcons and an analysis of their population that human intervention was not necessary in order for the population to recover and reach a steady point of equilibrium.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] This raises the question of should efforts on captive breeding and population establishment be done with human intervention or should efforts be carried out to prevent the source of the issue.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/captive-breeding] The efforts and finances used to help bring about new Peregrine Falcon populations could have been used to prevent some level of pollution or to help breeding effort for extinction-prone species who truly need intervention.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Chester Zoo is operated by the North of England Zoological Society, a registered charity founded in 1934.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The zoo receives no government funding and is the most-visited wildlife attraction in Britain with more than 2 million visitors in 2019.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] In 2007 *Forbes* described the zoo as one of the fifteen best zoos in the world.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] In 2017 and more recently, 2024, the zoo was named as the best zoo in the UK and as also regarded as the third best in the world by TripAdvisor.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The Mottershead family's market garden business was based in Shavington near Crewe.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] George Mottershead collected animals such as lizards and insects that arrived with exotic plants imported by the business.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] A visit to Belle Vue Zoo in Manchester as a boy in 1903 fuelled his developing interest in creating a zoo of his own.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Mottershead was wounded in the First World War and spent several years in a wheelchair.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Despite this, his collection of animals grew and he began to search for a suitable home for his zoo.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] He chose Oakfield Manor in Upton-by-Chester, which was a country village then but now is a suburb of Chester.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] He bought Oakfield Manor for £3,500 in 1930.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The house had 9 acres (3.6 ha) of gardens and provided easy access to the railways and to Manchester and Liverpool.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] There were local objections, but Mottershead prevailed, and Chester Zoo opened to the public on 10 June 1931.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The first animals were displayed in pens in the courtyard.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] An Ordnance Survey inch-a-mile map published in 1936 shows the area around as farmland and villages and marks the present Zoo area north of Oakfield as "Butter Hill".
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Rapid expansion followed after the Second World War, despite the difficulty of sourcing materials.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Mottershead had to be resourceful; the polar bear exhibit (1950) was built from recycled wartime road blocks and pillboxes.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] "Always building" was the zoo's slogan at the time.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Mottershead received the OBE, an honorary degree of MSc, and served as President of the International Union of Zoo Directors.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Mottershead wanted to build a zoo without the traditional Victorian iron bars to cage the animals.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] He was influenced by the ideas of Carl Hagenbeck, who invented the modern zoo concept and by Heini Hediger, a pioneer of ethology.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] At Chester, Mottershead took Hagenbeck's idea for moats and ditches as an alternative to cage bars, and extended their use throughout the zoo, often with species that Hagenbeck had not considered.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] For example, when chimpanzees were released into their new enclosure at Chester in 1956, a group of grassy islands, they were separated from visitors by no more than a 12-foot (3.7 m) strip of water.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] It turned out that they could not, and today the chimp islands are a centrepiece of Chester Zoo.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] In 1986 the zoo was enclosed with a fence, in line with the Zoo Licensing Act 1981.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Realm of the Red Ape, an Indonesian-forest-themed exhibit, featuring threatened Sumatran and Bornean orangutan, opened in May 2007.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] In January 2009, Chester Zoo unveiled Natural Vision, a £225 million plan to transform itself into the largest conservation attraction in Europe.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] It included a water ride to take visitors through the exhibit.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Natural Vision was to eventually include a 90-room hotel, a Conservation College, and a revamped main entrance that would link the zoo to a marina to be developed on zoo land, all to be completed by 2018.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Plans went before the public for comment in June 2009.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The projected Heart of Africa bio-dome, along with plans for the hotel, were shelved in 2011 due to the loss of £40m potential funding when the North West Regional Development Agency was abolished.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] In December 2012, planning permission was gained for a later phase of the Natural Vision masterplan.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] One of the largest zoo developments in Europe, Islands at Chester Zoo is a £40 million redevelopment project to extend the zoo's footprint and recreate six island habitats of Southeast Asia.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] A 600,000 square foot nature reserve was opened in April 2018.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The reserve sits outside the boundary of the main zoo and is free for people to enter.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] In October 2018, two Indian elephant calves (Nandita, aged three years, and Aayu, aged 18 months), died of elephant endotheliotropic herpesvirus (EEHV).
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] From 1995 on, this virus disease has caused many deaths of Indian elephants across the world in zoos and in the wild.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] On 15 December 2018, an electrical fault caused a fire to break out at the Monsoon Forest Habitat.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The zoo had to be evacuated and was closed.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Fifteen fire crews attended the zoo along with two rapid response units and an ambulance.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] All mammals were accounted for and one person was treated for the effects of smoke inhalation.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Some birds, frogs, fish and small insects were killed in the blaze.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The zoo reopened on Sunday 16 December 2018.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Chester Zoo monorail was an internal transport system for visitors from 1991 to 2019, but was closed, as it had become unreliable and covered less than half the zoo due to the zoo's expansion to over 125 acres (51 ha).
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Land from the monorail was to be used for a new attraction called Heart of Africa, an open African savannah habitat and vulture aviary.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] In March 2024, Chester Zoo announced the arrival of two snow leopards as part of a global conservation breeding programme.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The zoo also announced the opening of a new Himalayan habitat for two big cats.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The habitat is also home to red pandas, and a number of birds, including Himalayan monals.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] In July 2025, the zoo announced the birth of its first snow leopard cub, a female named Bheri.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The Heart of Africa exhibit opened in April 2025.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The 22.5 acre (nine hectare) savannah exhibit is designed to replicate the grasslands of Africa.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The exhibit houses 57 species, including giraffes, zebras, naked mole-rats and 15,000 locusts.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The zoo are also, at the same time, developing The Reserve Hotel project, a collection of 51 lodges, restaurant and access into the zoo.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The North of England Zoological Society (NEZS) is the organisation that runs Chester Zoo.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] It was formed in 1931 by the zoo's founder, George Mottershead.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The zoo is managed by a team led by CEO Jamie Christon DL and he reports to the Board of Trustees.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Christon is tasked with focusing on the unified strategy which supports the Strategic Development Plan and Conservation Plan.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The plan includes the development of Heart of Africa, The Reserve Hotel, new education facilities, The Square wedding venue, and from 2028 the development of African Forests.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The executive focuses on education change and DEAI through its people and culture.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Chester Zoo leads in public affairs and has influenced heavily at the heart of UK government.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The zoo employs over 650 permanent staff, increasing to over 1,000 during the main summer period.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The zoo is bisected by a public bridleway, Flag Lane (formerly the Millennium Cycle Path).
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] For many years, a single bridge (now called Elephants' Bridge), drivable by zoo vehicles and powered wheelchairs, near the elephant exhibit was the only crossing place within the grounds.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] A second crossing, passable by pedestrians and mobility scooters, called Bats' Bridge, opened in April 2008 near the Twilight Zone (now called Fruit Bat Forest), has improved the ability of visitors to circulate.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The opening of the new bridge also meant that visitors are now able to view on foot animals that were previously visible only from the monorail, as well as panoramic views of the zoo itself.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] For a long time, the public entrance was at the east end off Caughall Road.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] In the summer of 1995, the public entrance moved to the north side with dedicated access off the A41 Chester By-Pass.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] A brown sign which gave visitors directions to the new entrance was installed at the junction of the former entrance, and curiously, it remained there until the 2010s.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Thus, the zoo is entered in the 'newer' part west of Flag Lane, near the elephants, and the old car parks at the east end are being built over with service, admin and educational buildings.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The new entrance was re-modelled in 2012 to commemorate the Queen's Diamond Jubilee.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The zoo owns land outside the public area, and uses that land to grow food for its herbivorous animals.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Chester's catering facilities include Bembé Kitchen (formerly the Tsavo Café) near the main entrance which opened in 2006 to replace the former Oasis Café (formerly Mpila Snack Bar until the early 1980s).
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] June's Pavilion (formerly the Jubilee Café and latterly the Ark Restaurant) is on the west of the zoo and Manado Street Kitchen is found on Sulawesi in the Islands exhibit.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The Oakfield is a restaurant in a Victorian mansion house near the lion enclosure, and along with the Acorn Bar, are both used for private functions as well as catering to zoo visitors.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] There are three locations for food and drink in the Heart of Africa exhibit, including Pamoja Village.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] There are children's play areas, shops, kiosks and several picnic lawns around the zoo.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] A second pedestrian entrance is located in the southeast corner of the zoo behind Oakfield House.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] In 2025, the zoo was divided into colour zones to ease navigating the expansive site.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The Yellow Zone includes the zoo's elephants, monkeys, bats and spectacled bears.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The Pink Zone includes the Islands exhibit, housing animals such as southern cassowaries, Sumatran tigers and binturongs.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The Orange Zone includes the Heart of Africa exhibit, housing eastern black rhinoceros, meerkats and flamingos.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The Green Zone includes The Spirit of the Jaguar exhibit, as well as chimpanzees, aye-ayes, okapis and sloths.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The Blue Zone includes the Dragons in Danger habitat, Himalayas and Madagascar, featuring animals such as lemurs, snow leopards and Komodo dragons.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Chester Zoo holds one of the largest and most diverse zoological collections in the UK with around 30,000 animals from over 500 species.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The collection includes representatives from all the vertebrate classes as well as many invertebrate groups.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Rare species on exhibit include Persian onager, Coquerel's sifaka, great hornbill, Boelen's python and tuatara.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] For all these species, among others, Chester Zoo is the only UK holder.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] At the end of 2007, over half the species at the Zoo appeared on the IUCN Red List and 155 were classified as threatened species.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] 134 species were kept as part of a managed captive breeding programme.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The Zoo manages the studbooks for Congo buffalo, jaguar, blue-eyed cockatoo, Madagascan tree boa, gemsbok (all ESB species), eastern black rhinoceros, Ecuadorian amazon parrot, Mindanao writhe-billed hornbill, Sumatran tiger and Rodrigues flying fox (all EEP species).
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] At the end of 2015, Chester Zoo became the first zoo outside of New Zealand to breed the tuatara.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Heart of Africa opened in 2025 and is the largest zoo habitat ever created in the UK.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The expansive 22.5 acre exhibit is home to 57 species, including 15,000 locusts, a flock of 107 greater flamingos, critically endangered vultures, and a colony of naked mole rats.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Built around a large open savannah with multiple species living side by side, the exhibit is also the new home to the zoo's Northern giraffes, African wild dogs and sees the return of Grevy's zebra to the zoo.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The indoor habitat, Hidden Savannah, houses 11 cold-blooded species including the African bullfrog and red spitting cobra, as well as critically endangered pancake tortoises.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Hidden Savannah is also home to small mammals such as Karoo short-eared sengi and pygmy mice.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The Zoo's Eastern black rhinoceros exhibit, originally opened in 2003 as the Tsavo Rhino Experience, has been incorporated into Heart of Africa.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The exhibit is modelled on the Tsavo National Park in Kenya.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The Zoo has a successful rhinoceros breeding programme with ten calves born between 2008 and 2018..
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The Zoo's latest rhino birth was a female calf, Lumi, in November 2023.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Opposite the black rhinoceros lies the Tsavo Aviary, a walk-through exhibit featuring a variety of African birds.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] It was originally opened in 2009 as the Tsavo Bird Safari, and is now incorporated into Heart of Africa.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] It currently houses von der decken's hornbills, lilac-breasted rollers, hammerkops, weaver birds and a variety of waterfowl, amongst other species.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The Zoo opened Islands in July 2015, a project which extended its footprint by 15 acres southwards to the A41 boundary.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Islands features species from the Philippines and Indonesia, areas where the Zoo is involved in in situ conservation programmes.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Visitors are able to walk through six themed "islands" (representing Panay, Papua, Bali, Sumatra, Sumba and Sulawesi) via a series of pathways, bridges and buildings.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The project also includes a boat ride, educational exhibits, play areas and a restaurant, the Manado Street Kitchen.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The exhibit opened in three phases between 2015 and 2017.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The second phase included Monsoon Forest, the UK's largest indoor zoo habitat, and the Sumatran tiger exhibit.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] In Monsoon Forest, visitors can view Sumatran orangutans, silvery gibbons, Sulawesi crested macaques, Sunda wrinkled hornbills, Sunda gharials and many other reptiles, amphibians, fish, invertebrates and free-flying birds.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The Zoo's critically endangered Sumatran tigers are a breeding pair.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Dash (male) and Kasarna (female) produced their first cubs in 2023.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The third phase included exhibits for Malayan sun bears, Palawan binturongs and Malayan tapirs, as well as a walk-through aviary featuring various Indonesian songbirds.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Chester Zoo currently holds five Asian elephants in a purpose-built breeding and research facility.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The group includes an elderly female (Maya, born in 1966), a mother and daughter pair (Karishma, born in 1998, and Elizabeth, born in 2016) and a young half-sibling pair (female Indali, born in 2016, and male Anjan, born in 2018).
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Maya arrived from Chessington World of Adventures in 1990 and Karishma and Elizabeth came from Whipsnade Zoo in 2025.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Indali and Anjan were both born at Chester Zoo.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Elephants of the Asian Forest was completed in two phases.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The outdoor exhibit was opened in 2000 and comprises a main paddock of 5,900m2, a bull yard of 550m2 and two holding pens of 270m2 each.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] A new building replacing the previous elephant house was completed in 2006 at a cost of £3 million.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] It is modelled on an Assamese rainforest and has a total footprint of 2,730m2.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] In addition to the elephant holding pens, the building contains exhibits for other indigenous Asian species, including great hornbills, azure-winged magpies, red-billed blue magpies, prevost's squirrels, belanger's tree shrews and northern Luzon giant cloud rats.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] There is also a 23,800 litre aquarium housing clown loach and tiger barbs.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Chester Zoo's history with Asian elephants dates back to 1941, when individuals evacuated from other British zoos during wartime were moved to Chester for their safety.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] A new elephant house opened in 1961 and was used to house both Asian and African elephants, as well as rhinoceroses, hippopotamuses and tapirs.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] In 1977, Chester became the first zoo in the UK to successfully breed the Asian species with the arrival of a calf named Jubilee.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Motty, a hybrid African-Asian elephant calf was born in July 1978, but died in infancy.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] He has been named by Guinness World Records as "the rarest elephant on record".
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Chester's Asian elephant herd has produced many more calves over the past 30 years, but several have succumbed to the deadly EEHV virus.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] In 2025, the zoo announced the development of a new vaccine which triggers the required immune response to protect elephants from EEHV.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The vaccine was developed in partnership with the University of Surrey and the Animal and Plant Health Agency and was trialled on adult elephants at Chester.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The next step is to conduct trials on younger elephants, which are at highest risk from the virus.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The zoo is bringing forward plans to increase the size of their elephant exhibit to meet the new minimum space requirements set out in the UK Government's 2025 animal welfare reforms.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] In 2008, Asian Plains received its official opening.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Based around a mixed-species paddock featuring Burmese brown-antlered deer, the exhibit has recently been extended to include new enclosures for greater one-horned rhinoceroses and cheetahs.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The male rhino was joined by a female in 2008 to form a pair which the zoo hoped would breed.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Sadly, in November 2009, the zoo's male Indian rhino, Patna, was put down due to a longstanding leg injury.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The zoo obtained a replacement male from Edinburgh Zoo in March 2010.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Since they were closely related, the previous female departed for a zoo in Spain shortly after, and the zoo are in the progress of creating a breeding situation – Baabu has now been exchanged for Beni from Plzeň Zoo.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The paddocks formerly housed barasingha, Ankole cattle blackbuck and sitatunga.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] A sandy paddock for Persian onagers lies in the centre of the Zoo.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] They formerly shared the space with Bactrian camels, but the camels have since moved to the old giraffe exhibit.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Zebra have also been displayed here in the past.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] A paddock which was only visible from the monorail but can now be seen from the Bats Bridge holds a group of Philippine spotted deer.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Cheetah returned to the Zoo in November 2025 with the arrival of a pair of one-year old brothers Kendi and Tafari from Yorkshire Wildlife Park.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The subspecies held by Chester is the critically-endangered Northeast African cheetah, with fewer than 500 estimated to remain in the wild.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The Zoo previously held cheetah between 2008 and 2024, with successful breeding taking place in 2011 and 2013.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The 6,000m2 cheetah habitat can be viewed from the elevated boardwalk leading to Bat's Bridge and from a sheltered viewing area styled on an African round hut.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Monkey Islands was opened in 1997, replacing the old monkey house, and is currently home to four monkey species: Colombian spider monkeys, mandrills, lion-tailed macaques and roloway monkeys.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Former inhabitants include golden-bellied capuchins, Campbell's mona monkeys, Sulawesi crested macaques and crested porcupines.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Visitors enter the monkey house and view the animals from a central corridor.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Each species has a glass-fronted indoor enclosure with climbing apparatus and an outdoor enclosure, moated and heavily planted.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Miniature Monkeys, opened in May 2004, consists of two enclosures.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The first is home to a pair of pied tamarins with pygmy marmosets, and the second is shared by three emperor tamarins and three golden-headed lion tamarins.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Geoffrey's marmosets, black-tailed marmosets, black lion tamarins, red titi monkeys and white-faced sakis have also been housed here in the past but have been moved out for various reasons.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Bears of the Cloud Forest opened in 2004 and is home to a pair of spectacled bears and other South American animals.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The purpose-built exhibit is designed to mimic the bear's natural habitat by providing trees and a rocky terrain.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Nearby are paddocks housing capybaras, giant anteaters, and Brazilian tapirs.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Guanacos and vicuñas were previously housed in this section, along with rheas.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Fruit Bat Forest is the largest free-flying bat cave in Europe.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The cave holds two species of bat: Rodrigues fruit bats, and Seba's short-tailed bats.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] It is also home to a varied collection of other species including, common tenrecs and blind cave fish.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The Zoo's lions are the endangered Asiatic subspecies, held as part of the European conservation breeding programme.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] They are exhibited in a 4,790 square metre enclosure which was completed in 2019 and is modelled on the Gir Forest in India, the only place Asiatic lions are found in the wild.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The zoo's current pair arrived in December 2025.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The male, Nilay, was born in Cologne Zoo in January 2024 and the female, Shanti, was born in London Zoo in March 2024.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Prior to their arrival, Chester had held a trio of lions (male Iblis and females Kiburi and Kumari) but they never produced cubs.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The last time the zoo bred lions was in 2007, when a single male cub, Tejas, was hand-reared by keepers.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] On the way to and from the lion habitat, visitors pass exhibits for domestic goats and the UK's only great hornbills.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The hornbill aviary previously held peafowl and Brahminy starlings.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Tropical Realm is Britain's largest tropical house at over 26,000 cubic metres.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Opened in 1964, most of the interior is an open-plan space extending to roof level and themed with pools and mature tropical plants, with pathways for visitors through the undergrowth.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Here, more than 30 species of birds are free-flying, including Nicobar pigeons, various species of starlings and ground birds such as crested partridges.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Aviaries and vivaria are arranged around the sides of the building; those on the upper level were originally designed for birds of paradise and the hornbill aviaries were originally made for gorillas.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] At the entrance is an aviary for Sumatran laughingthrushes and grey-winged blackbirds.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The Tropical Realm is also the centre of the reptile collection.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The crocodile pools (which formerly housed dwarf crocodiles, American alligators and Philippine crocodiles) currently house spectacled caimans in one and white-winged wood ducks in the other.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Near the entrance is an enclosure for tuataras.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] This lizard-like species from New Zealand is the last surviving sphenodont, a prehistoric group of reptiles, and Chester is the only British zoo to exhibit them.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] In February 2016, a tuatara hatched for the first time outside of New Zealand, leading Chester Zoo to be the only zoo to have bred them anywhere else.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] There were many varieties of snakes and lizards in the past (many had to depart as a result); rhinoceros ratsnakes, emerald tree boas and eyelash vipers now being the only remaining.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The lizard collection is now made up of serrated casquehead iguanas, green-crested Lizards, northern caiman lizards, and a Parson's chameleon.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Tortoises are represented by Galápagos and radiated tortoises with Vietnamese box turtles.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Amphibians include poison dart frogs, Golden mantellas, a Rio Cauca caecilian, false tomato frogs and Morelet's tree frogs.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] From late 2015 to early 2016, the former golden-bellied capuchin exhibit at the rear of Tropical Realm was converted into a nocturnal zone housing a pair of aye-ayes and a group of Malagasy giant rats.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The capuchin's moated outdoor exihibit is now home to a group of cottontop tamarins.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The northeast area of the zoo is where many forest-dwelling species are kept.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] As well as the chimpanzees, okapis, jaguars, condors and Tropical Realm, there are enclosures for Congo buffaloes, and red river hogs.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Nearby is a large paddock and house for domestic Bactrian camels, which used to hold the Zoo's giraffes before their move to Heart of Africa in 2025.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The area between the rear of Tropical Realm and the Spirit of the Jaguar has enclosures for various species including a group of native sand lizards, and a mixed enclosure for red-billed curassows and Inca Jays.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] In 2008 the Zoo opened Butterfly Journey, a heated butterfly and invertebrate house which features free-flying butterflies and moths and free-roaming millipedes and frogs.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Exotic species on show include blue morphos, giant owls, glasswings, swallowtails and Atlas moths), as well as a cabinet of cocoons and a caterpillar hatchery.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] A row of vivariums near the exit door hold a variety of invertebrates, including stick insects, hissing cockroaches and katydids.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Animals formerly displayed in Forest Zone include maned wolves, babirusa, warthogs, Mallorcan midwife toads, golden-bellied capuchins, visayan warty pigs and ring-tailed coatis.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Formerly the camel house, this enclosure adjoining the giraffe house was remodelled in 2006 to house okapis.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Initially two males were kept: Dicky arrived from Marwell Wildlife in 2005 and Mbuti came from Bristol Zoo in the same year.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] In 2006, Dicky left for London Zoo to make way for a female named Stuma from Germany.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] In 2009, Mbuti and Dicky were swapped back, with Mbuti going to London Zoo and Dicky coming back to Chester.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Other animals that can be seen here include Red forest duikers, Gambian pouched rats, butterfly barbs, Gaboon vipers and short-eared elephant shrews.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Mount Kulal spiny mice and Mesic four-striped grass mice have also been kept here in the past along with various other small species.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The Okapi bred for the first time in 2012, producing a female calf named Tafari.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The success was repeated in 2014 with the birth of a new male calf.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] This pavilion was opened in 1989 by Diana, Princess of Wales and Countess of Chester, and is home to 26 Western chimpanzees.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] This is the largest colony of chimps in Europe, housed in the Roundhouse, a conical indoor enclosure linked to an outside moated island.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The island is planted with many bushes and has large poles for the chimps to climb on.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The inside area has a climbing frame that allows the chimps to stay close together on several levels of platform.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] There are seven interconnected off-show dens.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Spirit of the Jaguar opened in 2001 and was designed by McCormick Architecture.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] It features exhibits for jaguars and other species from the Amazon rainforest.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The exhibit was updated in 2011 to focus on human/wildlife conflict.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The jaguar exhibit can hold up to four cats and is split into two sections, each with an indoor and outdoor space.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The indoor areas are modelled on a rainforest and a dry savannah and the outdoor areas contain climbing features and pools for behavioural enrichment.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] It is currently home to three jaguars: female Bonita and her son Remi occupy the first section and melanistic female Inka occupies the second.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Spirit of the Jaguar is also home to Linnaeus's two-toed sloths, Azara's agouti and a variety of amphibians, fish and invertebrates.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] A centrepiece open-topped aquarium features numerous Amazonian fish including red-bellied piranhas and shoals of tetra.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Realm of the Red Ape is a £3.5 million extension to the existing orangutan house, home to Bornean orangutans, and was the most expensive capital project in the zoo's history before the construction of Islands.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The exhibit opened to the public on 26 May 2007 after a two-year construction period.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] It comprises a new two-story building linked to the existing orangutan house with three indoor and two outdoor enclosures, providing accommodation for a larger number of apes.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The outdoor areas can be viewed from a first floor public gallery and feature mesh roofs supported by tree-like structures which act as climbing frames for the apes.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] A further enclosure houses a group of lar gibbons.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Animals and plants from Indonesia are exhibited inside Realm of the Red Ape in a rainforest-themed setting.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Birds on display include blue-crowned hanging parrots, Timor sparrows, chestnut-backed thrushes, roul-roul partridges, superb fruit doves and black-naped fruit doves.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Crocodile monitors, reticulated pythons, red-tailed racers, Bell's Angle-Head Lizards, Chinese water dragons, emerald tree monitors, white-lipped tree vipers and green tree pythons feature among the reptiles.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Invertebrates include Rhinoceros beetles, giant walking sticks, common crow butterflies, jungle nymphs, praying mantises, Malaysian Katydids and leaf insects.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The zoo's Sumatran orangutans were relocated from Realm of the Red Ape to a new exhibit in the Islands development during January 2016.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The former Caribbean flamingo exhibit has been redeveloped as a mixed-species netted aviary for Latin American wetland birds.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The new exhibit opened in June 2021, coinciding with the Zoo's 90th anniversary.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Visitors enter the aviary along a walkway and viewing platform which project out over a lake, giving uninterrupted views of the birds.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] In addition to the 100-strong flock of flamingos, the aviary is home to scarlet ibises, roseate spoonbills, black-necked stilts, Orinoco geese, Muscovy ducks, ringed teals, black-bellied whistling ducks, saffron finches and other waterfowl species.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] In early 2010, the zoo's California sea lions left the collection.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] During this time, the pool was converted to house a new species to the zoo.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The giant otters went on show for the first time on 26 March 2010.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] In the neighbouring enclosure, a large breeding group of over 50 Humboldt penguins have their own pool, and visitors can watch the birds from an underwater viewing window.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] This exhibit is primarily a herpetarium for the zoo's Komodo dragons, Jantan and Ora who arrived from Prague Zoo in 2014, originating from the Lesser Sunda Islands.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] It was opened in 1998 and extended in 2003 to include an outdoor enclosure used by the dragons in the warmer summer months.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The exhibit is built on the site of the zoo's former bird house.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] In 2007, several young baby Komodo dragons were put on display after one of the zoo's two females laid eggs which hatched although the female had not been mated; this is parthenogenesis, the first such case recorded in this species.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The exhibit was revamped in 2009 to house Caribbean iguanas in one section of the building.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] It now currently houses spiny turtles in one side and critically endangered mountain chicken frogs along with Caribbean hermit crabs in the other.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Dragons in Danger also houses various Indonesian and Philippine rainforest birds, such as Palawan peacock-pheasants, pheasant pigeons, Montserrat orioles and Visayan tarictic hornbills.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Recently added was a pair of Philippine mouse deer which have successfully bred.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Also housed here are Montserrat tarantulas, which Chester bred in 2016 for the first time in captivity.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Species formerly kept in the exhibit include Socorro doves, Mindanao bleeding-hearts, Papuan lorikeets and Saint Lucia parrots.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Opened in 2019 as Madagascar Forest, this development exhibits endangered species from Madagascar.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Themed displays also provide visitors with information on field conservation projects supported by the Zoo.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The 5,875m2 site is located in the centre of the zoo and was previously occupied by the Sumatran tiger exhibit and a large aviary for European birds (Europe on the Edge).
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Madagascar comprises three animal exhibits linked by winding visitor pathways.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The first and second exhibits house fossa, which bred for the first time at the zoo in 2022, and critically endangered Coquerel's sifaka.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The third and largest exhibit is a walkthrough lemur enclosure which houses ring tailed lemurs, red ruffed lemurs, crowned lemurs, red-bellied lemurs and black lemurs.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The Zoo's Himalayan habitat opened in March 2024 and is designed around a purpose-built, immersive exhibit for snow leopards.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The exihibit is modelled on the rocky terrain of the cat's natural habitat and includes rocky cliffs, air-cooled caves and two outdoor areas with glass viewing windows.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Male Nashin and female Nubra are the first snow leopards to be held at Chester and were sourced from European zoos as part of a global conservation breeding programme.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] They produced a female cub, Bheri, in 2025.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Other species on show in the Himalayan zone include red pandas and Lord Derby's parakeets.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Bordering the onager and cheetah habitats is a waterway running north-south along which the water bus formerly travelled, past island groups of white-faced sakis, Alaotran bamboo lemurs and howler monkeys.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] A variety of callitrichids, including cotton-top tamarins, were formerly housed on the Bamboo lemur Island, whilst the howler monkey and white-faced saki exhibits were formerly home to black-and-white ruffed lemurs and red ruffed lemurs.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] A nearby island viewable from Bats Bridge was previously home to lowland anoa and is now home to babirusa.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] In the southeast corner of the zoo are enclosures housing an assortment of animals, including red pandas, Southern pudu, Cabot's tragopans and the wetland bird nursery.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The former cassowary exhibit next to the anteaters was redeveloped in 2016.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Near the off-show Rare Parrot Breeding Centre is an aviary currently housing brown wood owls that was formerly home to macaws and keas.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The remainder of the zoo's owl collection are house in aviaries near June's Food Court and great green macaws can be found near the Tropical Realm.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] This was the zoo's largest aviary, and was one of the biggest in the UK.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] It was opened in 1993 on the site of the former polar bear enclosure.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] It housed a variety of European birds, including European black vultures and griffon vultures, and the rarer of the two European storks, the black stork.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Wading birds also featured, including spoonbills, ibises and egrets as well as a selection of waterfowl.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Smaller birds included rock doves, northern lapwings, red-legged partridges and the native but rare red-billed chough.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] It was demolished in 2019 to make way for Madagascar Forest.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] In 2011, a new exhibit housing African wild dogs on the site of the former Przewalski's horse paddock was opened.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] In the style of an African Research Station with an African Village, the exhibit has a dry landscape with fake kopje stones.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Joining the pack of African wild dogs in secondary exhibits are aardvarks and rock hyraxes.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The exhibit was incorporated into the Heart of Africa development in 2025 and the aardvark exhibit relocated.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The aquarium, built by George Mottershead's daughter and son-in-law, was a small, traditional building which opened to the public in 1952.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] It housed a varied collection of freshwater and marine fish, aquatic invertebrates and amphibians.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] It has had notable success breeding seahorses and achieved the first captive breeding of the freshwater motoro stingray.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Other notable fish include epaulette sharks, mudskippers and Lake Malawi cichlids.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The aquarium closed in September 2025 due to safety concerns raised by structural engineers.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] All fish and aquatic species were moved to new homes around the zoo or cared for behind the scenes.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The zoo has announced that a new aquarium will be developed on the site of the former orangutan house.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Marmot Mania opened in 2002 and housed prairie dogs.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] In 2010, dwarf mongooses replaced the prairie dogs and it was renamed Mongoose Mania.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The exhibit featured a network of tunnels beneath the enclosure through which children could crawl, then stand up in plastic domes to view the animals at eye level.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Prior to the mongoose and prairie dog exhibits, the area had been a children's petting farm (closed in 2001 after an outbreak of foot-and-mouth disease) and later a picnic lawn.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Prior to its redevelopment as Heart of Africa, the west side of the Zoo housed grass paddocks supporting grazing groups of Grevy's zebras, sitatunga, Kirk's dik-diks, scimitar-horned oryx, eastern bongos, lesser kudus and roan antelopes.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The zoo's Przewalski's horses left the collection in 2009 to make way for the African wild dog enclosure.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Other animals previously housed here included Père David's deer, red-necked wallabies, ostriches and emus.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The zoo has a service that gives people the option of adopting an animal of their choice, they are also given two complimentary tickets to allow them to visit the animals.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] They can also become members which allows them to visit Chester and a range of other zoos across the UK free of charge for a year.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] Every three months, members and adopters receive the zoo magazine on line, which provides updates and information about what is happening at the zoo.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] During summer 2007, television crews from Granada filmed at Chester for the documentary series *Zoo Days*, a behind the scenes look at the day-to-day running of the zoo, narrated by Jane Horrocks.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] British broadcast rights were sold to Five and the first 20-part series began airing on British terrestrial TV on 8 October 2007, transmitting on weekday evenings in a regular 6:30 pm slot.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] A second 20-part series of *Zoo Days* was swiftly commissioned and began airing on 3 March 2008.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The third 20-part series was broadcast from Colchester Zoo, before returning to Chester for the fourth 20-part series on 10 November 2008.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] In 2014 the zoo was the subject of BBC One drama *Our Zoo*, telling the story of the founding of Chester Zoo by the Mottershead family in the 1930s and featured Lee Ingleby as George Mottershead.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] During the six-part series, the show reached audiences in excess of five million viewers and was nominated for two national TV awards.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] In January 2016, Channel 4 began broadcasting a six-part series, *The Secret Life of the Zoo*, following the keepers and animals at Chester Zoo and narrated by Olivia Colman from Series 1 to 5 and Tamsin Grieg since Series 6.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The first series was a ratings success and was recommissioned for a second series.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/chester-zoo] The show has now run for ten seasons with a compilation series in 2020.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada] The **Committee on the Status of Endangered Wildlife in Canada** (**COSEWIC**, French: **Comité sur la situation des espèces en péril au Canada**, **COSEPAC**) is an independent committee of wildlife experts and scientists whose "raison d'être is to identify species at risk" in Canada.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada] It designates the conservation status of wild species.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada] It was established in 1977 to provide a single, scientifically sound classification of wildlife species at risk of extinction.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada] In the 2002 Species at Risk Act, COSEWIC was appointed as the body to identify and assess a species status.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada] Although the status assigned by COSEWIC is not legally binding, it does report its results to the government and the public.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada] The report is influential toward the addition of species to the List of Wildlife Species at Risk by the Minister of the Environment.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada] By December 2013 there were "686 wildlife species in various COSEWIC risk categories, including 196 Special Concern (SC), 166 Threatened (T), 302 Endangered (E), 22 Extirpated (XT) (i.e., no longer found in the wild in Canada) and 15 wildlife species that are Extinct (X).
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada] The other category is not at risk (NAR).
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada] COSEWIC provides online updated status reports on designated species.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada] COSEWIC bases its quantitative criteria for species' status assessment on the revised IUCN Red List, the world's most comprehensive inventory of the global conservation status of biological species.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/committee-on-the-status-of-endangered-wildlife-in-canada] COSEWIC provides International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN), the world's main authority on the conservation status of species, with a Regional Red List.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/distinct-population-segment] A **distinct population segment** (**DPS**) is the smallest division of a taxonomic species permitted to be protected under the U.S.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/distinct-population-segment] *Species*, as defined in the Act for listing purposes, is a taxonomic species or subspecies of plant or animal, or in the case of vertebrate species, a distinct population segment.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/distinct-population-segment] Three elements are considered in a decision regarding the status of a possible DPS as endangered or threatened under the Act.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/distinct-population-segment] The population segment's conservation *status* in relation to the Act's standards for listing (i.e., is the population segment, when treated as if it were a species, endangered or threatened?).
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/distinct-population-segment] It is delimited by international governmental boundaries within which differences in control of exploitation, management of habitat, conservation status, or regulatory mechanisms exist that are significant in light of section 4(a)(1)(D) of the Act.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/distinct-population-segment] In carrying out this examination, the Services [USFWS and NMFS] will consider available scientific evidence of the discrete population segment's importance to the taxon to which it belongs.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/distinct-population-segment] Evidence that the discrete population segment differs markedly from other populations of the species in its genetic characteristics.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/distinct-population-segment] Because precise circumstances are likely to vary considerably from case to case, it is not possible to describe prospectively all the classes of information that might bear on the biological and ecological importance of a discrete population segment.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/distinct-population-segment] If a population segment is discrete and significant (i.e., it is a distinct population segment) its evaluation for endangered or threatened status will be based on the Act's definitions of those terms and a review of the factors enumerated in section 4(a)of the Act.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/distinct-population-segment] It may be appropriate to assign different classifications to different DPSes of the same vertebrate taxon.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/distinct-population-segment] The Fish and Wildlife Service's Listing and Recovery Priority Guidelines (48 FR 43098; September 21, 1983) generally afford DPSes the same consideration as subspecies, but when a subspecies and a DPS have the same numerical priority, the subspecies receives higher priority for listing.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/distinct-population-segment] The Services will continue to generally accord subspecies higher priority than DPSes.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/distinct-population-segment] In consideration of Pacific salmon for listing under the Act, NMFS has relied on the evolutionarily significant unit (ESU) concept and previous developed a policy on the definition of species under the Act (56 FR 58612– 58618; November 20, 1991).
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/distinct-population-segment] The policy applies only to species of salmonids native to the Pacific.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/distinct-population-segment] Under this policy, a stock of Pacific salmon is considered a DPS if it represents an evolutionarily significant unit (ESU) of a biological species.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/distinct-population-segment] A stock must satisfy two criteria to be considered an ESU: (1) It must be substantially reproductively isolated from other conspecific population units; and (2) It must represent an important component in the evolutionary legacy of the species.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/distinct-population-segment] The 1996 joint policy considers the 1991 NMFS policy on Pacific salmon to be consistent with the joint policy, being a detailed extension of it.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/distinct-population-segment] The joint policy further states that NMFS will continue to exercise the 1991 policy with respect to Pacific salmonids.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/eaza-ex-situ-programme] The **EAZA Ex-situ Programme (EEP)** is a population management and conservation programme by European Association of Zoos and Aquaria (EAZA) for wild animals living in captivity in European zoos and aquaria.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/eaza-ex-situ-programme] The programme was formerly known as the European Endangered Species Programme.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/eaza-ex-situ-programme] Each EEP has a coordinator who is assisted by a species committee.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/eaza-ex-situ-programme] Together with the EAZA Species Committee, recommendations are made each year about relocating and breeding animals, and the conditions of such a move (breeding loan, exchange, term free disposition, etc.).
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/eaza-ex-situ-programme] Even though EEP participation is mainly reserved for EAZA zoos, it is possible for non-EAZA collections to be included in these programmes.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/eaza-ex-situ-programme] There are generally however more restrictions on such zoos (which may go as far as only holding non-breeding animals for educational purposes), and on the number of programmes they may participate in.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/eaza-ex-situ-programme] For zoo visitors to have the opportunity to see how wild animals look, live, and behave, zoos must ensure that truly wild animals, with all of their natural characteristics, are presented.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/eaza-ex-situ-programme] Zoo animals are vulnerable to three very serious breeding problems inherent to small, artificial populations: inbreeding depression, loss of genetic variability, and accumulation of deleterious mutations.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/eaza-ex-situ-programme] These problems can easily result in loss of original wild traits, and in the expression of heritable abnormalities.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/eaza-ex-situ-programme] If what was once a pure, wild population of animals deteriorates through generations of uncontrolled breeding into inferior or partially domesticated stock, then the animals are no longer suitable for any conservation effort, and the zoos have failed to perform an important educational task.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/eaza-ex-situ-programme] The effects of breeding captive populations of wild animals over periods of many generations have been well studied.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/eaza-ex-situ-programme] Based on these studies and genetic theory, guidelines for breeding such small populations have been developed.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/eaza-ex-situ-programme] Following such guidelines should sharply reduce possibilities of breeding problems and concurrently should maximize the number of generations in which the original founding diversity can be maintained.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/eaza-ex-situ-programme] The application of these guidelines, and many others tailored to specific populations, results in strictly controlled breeding programmes in which nothing is left to chance.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/eaza-ex-situ-programme] Only in this manner can healthy and truly wild populations be maintained over a period of one or two hundred years.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/eaza-ex-situ-programme] Such strict control is entirely dependent on cooperation among zoos that hold individuals of the species, as single zoos generally do not have the facilities to maintain a population of adequate size independently.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/eaza-ex-situ-programme] As of 2022, over 400 animal species are represented in the EAZA Ex-situ Programme.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/eaza-ex-situ-programme] One species which has been handled by EEP was Sumatran tiger which have only a few hundred left in the wild, and only about 7% of their habitat remains.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/eaza-ex-situ-programme] They used to live in all the Sumatran territory, but nowadays most of them can only be found in the mountain regions of the Burit Barisan volcanic area.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/eaza-ex-situ-programme] This species is currently threatened with the destruction of habitat and poaching, for trade of its parts in traditional oriental medicine or as a trophy.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/eaza-ex-situ-programme] The Tiger EEP has made contributions to the conservation of Amur and Sumatran tigers in the wild, via fundraising for wild tiger conservation projects, raising awareness and providing educational opportunities, and assisting with relevant research and training.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/eaza-ex-situ-programme] For example, in November 2011, Sumatran tiger Kirana has delivered three cubs at Chester Zoo under EEP which attempts to coordinate breeding between zoos and maintain genetic diversity.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/eaza-ex-situ-programme] The Gorilla EEP is one of the most intensively managed and oldest breeding programmes in European zoos.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/eaza-ex-situ-programme] The Gorilla EEP was started in 1987 and was run by the Frankfurt Zoological Garden, who continue to maintain the Gorilla Studbook.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/eaza-ex-situ-programme] In the past decade, some major improvements have been achieved in the management of the EEP for the western lowland gorilla *Gorilla gorilla gorilla*.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/eaza-ex-situ-programme] Neonatal mortality and hand‐rearing rates have decreased; transfers in most cases proved to be successful: almost all gorillas were integrated into their new groups and most animals introduced to a breeding group had their first offspring within two years.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/eaza-ex-situ-programme] The results show that the current management approach is successful, and that the population is sustainable and has good genetic health.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/eaza-ex-situ-programme] Just the incongruencies in laws can sometimes make exchange of specimens for breeding purposes by two closely situated zoos a formidable task if a border happens to lie between them.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/eaza-ex-situ-programme] Yet successes have been achieved: the growth of the EEP has been considerable since its initiation in 1985.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/eaza-ex-situ-programme] EAZA has more than 400 member institutions in 47 countries throughout Europe, Western Asia and beyond.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/eaza-ex-situ-programme] EAZA currently manages EEPs for over 500 different species.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/eaza-ex-situ-programme] More than 300 EAZA members were participating in EEP programmes in 2021.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/eaza-ex-situ-programme] EEP is one of the worldwide assembly of such regional breeding programs in zoos for threatened species.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/eaza-ex-situ-programme] The North America counterpart is the Species Survival Plan, and Australian, Japanese, Indian, and Chinese zoos also have similar programs.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/eaza-ex-situ-programme] Combined, there are now many hundred zoos worldwide involved in regional breeding programs.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] The Endangered Species Act (ESA) was first passed in 1973 and forms the basis of biodiversity and endangered species protection in the United States.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] The original purpose of the Endangered Species Act of 1973 was to prevent species endangerment and extinction due to the human impact on natural ecosystems.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] The three most powerful sections of the ESA are Sections 4, 7 and 9.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] Section 4 allows the Secretaries of Interior and Commerce to list species as threatened or endangered based on best available data.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] Section 7 requires federal agencies to consult with Fish and Wildlife Service (FWS) or National Marine Fisheries Service (NMFS) before taking any action that may threaten a listed species.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] Section 9 forbids the taking of an endangered species.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] The first amendment to the ESA was passed by the 95th United States Congress in 1978 to "introduce some flexibility into the Endangered Species Act".
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] The snail darter case was an important test case of the ESA because it made Congress realize how powerful the ESA really was.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] In 1966, the Tennessee Valley Authority began construction on the Tellico Dam on the Little Tennessee River.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] For years, environmentalists tried to shut down the project, but their actions were unsuccessful until the discovery of the snail darter, a small fish that feeds off aquatic snails.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] The snail darter was listed as an endangered species in 1975 and part of the Little Tennessee River was designated as critical habitat.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] The completion of the Tellico Dam threatened the survival of the snail darter, which was thought to be native only to the Little Tennessee River.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] In 1976, battle in the courts between the Tennessee Valley Authority and environmentalists began over the fate of the snail darter.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] Over the next three years, the decision was appealed all the way to the Supreme Court.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] Supreme Court ruled in favor of protecting the species "whatever the cost".
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] The Endangered Species Act was clear in stating that no federal project should be exempt from the provisions of Section 7.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] Starting in the spring of 1977, members of Congress made several attempts to pass legislation that weakened the ESA.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] Many large business interest groups, including the mining and timber industries, also spoke out against the power of the ESA.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] Beginning in April 1978, the Senate Subcommittee on Resources Protection began debating and developing a bill that would create a committee with power to exempt federal actions from Section 7 requirements.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] On April 12, 1978 Senator John Culver (D-IA) and Senate Minority Leader Howard Baker (R-TN) introduced a bill that would create a seven-member Cabinet-level committee with the authority to exempt a federal agency from Section 7 requirements.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] Meanwhile, in Wheatland, Wyoming, a consortium of energy utilities were attempting to build the Grayrocks Dam on the Laramie River to supply a coal-fired power plant.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] Upset that water diversion would threaten the critically endangered whooping crane, on October 2, 1978, the Nebraska Attorney General’s office obtained a federal injunction barring the dam.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] Grayrocks, however, enjoyed strong support in Congress, and by October 14 Teno Roncalio (D-WY) convinced the House to pass a bill exempting the dam from all federal regulation.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] In lieu of that, Senator Culver (D-IA) adapted the bill to his own attempts to exempt the snail darter, creating the Endangered Species Committee and required the committee to decide on an exemption from protections of the snail darter and the whooping crane within 30 days.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] Both the House of Representatives and Senate voted to amend the ESA, and on November 10 President Jimmy Carter signed the amendment into law.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] On December 4, Nebraska reached a settlement under which the power utilities would get to build Grayrocks dam by agreeing to purchase some habitat for the whooping crane.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] On January 23, 1979, the Endangered Species Committee met for the first time, refused to exempt the snail darter from protection, and granted Grayrocks an exemption from the whooping crane protections.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] The most important change that was brought about by the 1978 amendment was the creation of the Endangered Species Committee, known as the "God Squad" because of the substantial impact of its decisions on the natural world.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] One or more temporary members, sharing a single vote, may also be appointed by the President to represent any states that are affected by the exemption in question.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] This committee has the authority to exempt a project or action from Section 7 requirements, which otherwise prohibit actions that are "likely to jeopardize the continued existence" of a listed species or its habitat.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] To exempt an action, at least five members must vote in favor of the exemption.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] 4. neither the federal agency or the exemption applicant made irreversible commitment to the resources.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] Additionally, mitigation efforts must be taken to reduce the negative effects on the endangered species.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] The amendments also contain provisions for the Secretary of Defense or the President to authorize exemptions, in cases of national security or disaster situations respectively.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] Conversely, the Secretary of State may overrule exemptions if they are found to violate any international treaties.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] In 1991, a federal judge ordered the halting of logging on Pacific Northwest national lands because of the threat to the northern spotted owl.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] Following this action, the Bureau of Land Management (BLM) filed for exemption from Section 7.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] The northern spotted owl is a medium-sized bird that is dependent on old-growth forest and large territories for survival.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] The BLM came up with a solution that allowed logging to continue in the area, which included the sale of timber on 44 timber tracts to the logging industry.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] The 44 tracts totaled 4400 acres (18 km2) of land.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] The God Squad convened and discussed the issue.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] In a 5:2 vote, the God Squad voted for approval of the exemption in thirteen of the sales where there was no reasonable alternative to the sale.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] However, the exemption was soon overturned when Judge Stephen Reinhardt on the Ninth Circuit Court of Appeals found it had been illegal for the President to talk to his cabinet about the exemption.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] The environmentalists and the BLM agreed on a compromise that allowed the timber sale to continue.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] The BLM would develop a Long Range Forest Management Plan that would need to be approved by the FWS before any future timber sales.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] When the Clinton administration came into office, they withdrew the exemption request and convened a conference resulting in appointment of the Forest Ecosystem Management Assessment Team (FEMAT).
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] The FEMAT was created to develop a plan to protect the owl while still maintaining logging and forest management across the region.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] FEMAT and the Clinton administration agreed to protect 10 million acres (40,000 km2) of old growth forest for the owl, while limiting logging to 1 billion board feet (2,400,000 m3) per year.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] On March 31, 2026, a meeting of the God Squad voted to exempt oil and gas mining companies operating in the Gulf of Mexico from the Endangered Species Act, on unspecified national security grounds.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] The decision was requested by US Secretary of Defense Pete Hegseth.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] A similar announcement earlier in the month resulted in a lawsuit that adequate public notice was not provided.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] Environmental advocates were concerned the decision could cause the extinction of Rice's whale, which only lives in the Gulf of Mexico and is critically endangered after population loss caused by the Deepwater Horizon oil spill.
[src:eaza-ex-situ-programme/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] This decision overrides mitigation measures such as slowing down boats in whale habitat, keeping a safe distance from whales, and using quieter air guns for seismic surveys.
